SENTENCE: Til Naadens Dør og banke paa
At jeg med Synd og Ondskabs Dynd
Har smittet mig, saa knap hos sig
Ei veed jeg paa de Synder Tal,
I Sind og Hu mig rinder;
Guds Søn det alt har vel betalt,
Men jeg gik ei den snævre Vei,
At kun med blotte Læbers Ord,
Som flød til mig saa rundelig
Du har saa tidt med Kæmpeskridt
Men selv jeg lukket har min Dør,
Tidt banked paa og sagde: hør!
Din Ven staaer for dit Kammer.
I Veir og Vind, slog af mit Sind
Det var Gjengjæld, om du i Kvæld
Naar mig i Hjertet ret derpaa
Jeg hartad fra mig selv vil gaae,
Hvad Helved er, hvad Helveds Hær
Din Skabning det ei sømmer sig,
Saa reent vanslægted jeg fra dig,
Og med et Gran af Tale sand
Om Gunst ei maa for Retten gaae,
Her finder du en fattig Sjæl,
O Naadesol, jeg for din Stol
I Støv for dig nedkaster mig
I Barmen, Jesus! du hos dig
Som du for Alle og for mig
O lad derved mig finde Fred
O ræk min Sjæl fra Naadens Væld
Sørger ei for dem, der sove
Med Guds Fred i Gravens Skjød!
Til den Sal, som synker ei.
At naar han, i Sky forklaret,
Vinker saa fra Mark og By
Skal i Himlens Glands og Ære
Lad, Jesu! lad din naadefulde Lære
Os altid dyrebar og hellig være:
Thi den er salig, som oprigtig lyder,
Din Lærdom ene kan vor Siel bevæbne
Med Haab og Mod og Trøst i hver en Skiebne
Thi den bebuder, at vor Gud og Fader
Vor Fader Markens Græs saa yndig klæder,
Han Føde for det mindste Kryb bereder;
Han mig ei glemmer, naar jeg paa ham haaber,
O! vel mig, om jeg tro til Enden bliver,
Og tillidsfuld til Gud mig overgiver;
Da skal min Jesus visselig mig lede
Er jeg end ikke reen for Feil og Synder,
Dog Jesu blide Lærdom Trøst forkynder;
Thi Gud ved ham er mig en naadig Fader,
Saa skal da Jesu naadefulde Lære
Mig evig dyrebar og hellig være:
Hielp, Herre, hielp mig, at jeg trofast lyder,
For Øren da brat det ringed dem,
Det rørte dem alle saa underlig,
Der taltes om dem i Himmerig,
Der taltes om dem, som Livets Ord
Da hørtes paa Zion der Suus og Bruus,
Med Kraft fra det Høie det lave Huus
Da saaes der Tunger som Ild og Glød,
Guds Venner de fløi i Munden,
Paa alle Folks Tunger Guds Ord gjenlød,
Saa tændtes paa Jorden det Lys fra Gud,
Og har vi til nu paa det store Ord
Af Himmelens Ild som kom til Jord,
Vi har dog en Gnist annammet.
Den Gnist, den ulmer hos os endnu,
Saa gladelig rinder det os i Hu,
Tænk, det var saa tung en Vei!
Naar du, som han, vandre skal
Kom i Hu, han har bered
Naar jeg skal gaae ad den Vei,
Send mig din den gode Aand,
Tag min Sjæl udi din Haand!
Og takker dig, af Hjertet inderlig
Og det Forbund paa Salighedens Grund,
Som du med mig har gjort
Som mit Skjold jeg for mig bær
Et helligt Liv, en salig Død
De to maa ikke skilles ad,
Den ene gjør den anden glad,
At have stridt den gode Strid
Paa Troens Vei til sidste Tid,
Hvor er det sødt i Døden!
Vel den, sin Herre tro har tjent,
Sin Gjerning gjort, sit Løb fuldendt
Og bort i Fred kan fare!
Du prydet har din Tid og Stand
Al Verdens Frelser var din Skat,
At tjene Herren Dag og Nat,
Og naaede paa den trange Sti
Hvad Under da, at Gravens Bo
Du gik til Dødens Port saa fro
Du tog din Jesum sødt i Favn,
Saa reiste du i Herrens Navn
O, Jesus er endnu at faae,
Har vi ei skjønnet ret derpaa,
For den udi den sande Tro
Stod Jesus op af Jordens Skjød
Som Fuglechor i Mark og Lund
Saa alle Tunger trindt om Land
Som Blomster alle staae i Flor,
Saa blomstrer Alt i Jesu Navn
Du blev hos os i Støvets Land
Du blev hos os i Jesu Navn,
Er tidt dog i hans Fødestavn
Du er Guds Røst paa Livets Vei,
Saa uden dig vor Jesus ei
Men blev det klart for os endnu,
Og bede vi: Guds Aand, vær du
Ak nei, vi neppe tænke paa,
Skal du i Faders Sted os staae,
Vi og maae troe, han er i dig,
Vi skal ei raabe: kom til os!
Som du var i det Fjerne,
Men sukke: Synd og Død til Trods,
Guds Aand! bliv hos os gjerne,
For Jesu Skyld, som dig har sendt
Vil over dem, i dig erkjendt,
Ja, bliv hos os, vor Trøstermand!
Opliv hos os hver Tale sand,
Thi han er ei de Dødes Gud,
Til du gaaer fra Gud Fader ud
Hver Gang du hører Herrens Ord
Som det blev mumlet under Jord,
O, tag det op, udtal det ret,
Til os kom Godt fra Nazareth,
Hver Gang en ærlig Sjæl paa Jord
I Jesu Navn, men Bønnens Ord
Viis, du paa Alt kan bøde!
Og hvisk til os dit Fadervor,
At komme dig vor Gud ihu,
For Ro og Fred For Kjærlighed
Af Luft og Vand, Af Skov og Land
O Gud, hvor Mangen vanker om
Hvis fattig Haand er ofte tom,
Hvor Mangen staaer I Værk og Saar
Og raaber paa En Bid at faae
O, lad os ei vor Brødkurv hen
Før den, som tyede til os hen
Vort Forraads Tal Ei mindskes skal,
Gud signe os i Jesu Navn,
Vi gaae nu til vort Værk og Gavn
Velsign vor Daad, Lad Armods Graad
Men gid vi maae Den Kunst forstaae,
Naar da i Verden intet Brød
Gid da imellem Liv og Død
Gid vi vor Aand Da i din Haand,
Saa gjennem Død Til Hvile sød
Du mit Liv mit Haab, min Tro,
Dig skee Lov og Tak og Ære,
End jeg selv fra første Rod,
Du har havt mit Leer i Hænder
Seer mig heelt i Hjertet ind,
Jeg det jo af dig modtager.
Om du mig ei Alt tilskikker
Om en Sorg i Barmen stikker,
Du det lige godt kan mage.
Taget, som har gjemt min Lyst,
Om jeg selv blandt døde Frænder
Gaaer med Sorg og Død i Bryst
Du, min Gud, mig ikke slipper!
Hvad du giver, glad jeg tager,
Priser dig, mens jeg er til,
Som din Haand mig række vil;
Hvad der kommer, bedst mig baader,
Thi i Alt dit Hierte raader!
Manden i Muld, som er baaret og født af en Kvinde,
Han er fra Hulen opsteget til Himlenes Tinde,
Øiet af Muld overskuer nu Stjernernes Vange,
Øret af Muld sig forlyster med Englenes Sange,
Det er fuldbragt! saa herligt lyder
O denne Røst i Hiertet gyder
Haab, Glæde, Mod og himmels Trøst.
Bort nu al Frygt min Frelser vandt,
Og jeg en evig Redning fandt
Hvo vil mig nu for Gud anklage?
Naar jeg kun Synden vil forsage,
Min Jesus! frelses jeg ved dig;
Thi Dødens Vold og Gravens Magt
Det er fuldbragt du hisset troner
Og ved dit Ord du fører dem
O Frelser! dan mit Sind og Hierte,
Og leve som dit Ord mig lærte,
Og som din Vandel viste mig.
Da skal jeg hisset evig fro
Solen og Maanen og Stjernernes Hære
Vise os, hvad dine Hænder formaae,
Men i dit Huus, i din Kirke paa Jorden,
Der tale Dage med Dage om dig,
Der sig forklare din Sol og din Torden,
Der paa Oplysning selv Natten er rig!
Ei er i Sandhed der Ord eller Tanke
Som i dit Huus jo fik Mæle og Røst,
Og alt saa vide, som Stjernerne vanke,
Bringe paa Jord de Oplysning og Trøst,
Ordet med Solen i skiftende Tider
Udgaaer som Brudgom i morgenrød Glands,
Straalende frem ad sin Bane det skrider,
Krones som Helten med aftenrød Krands!
Saa paa sin Bane din Sol i det Høie,
Lyset i Sandhed, omreiser vor Jord,
Intet i Verden er skjult for dens Øie,
Reen som et Guld er den Lov, du har givet,
Trofast dit Vidnesbyrd fører til Livet,
Viismænd det gjør af vankundige Smaa!
For enhver, som paa dig bier,
Er og Frelser du af Gavn,
I dit Navn Guds Engle knæle!
Fra al Synd og fra Guds Vrede,
Fra al Sjælens Tørst og Sult,
Fra al Verdens Sorg og Nød,
Evig det hos mig skal boe,
Skjuler mig for Synd og Død,
Stol du kun paa dit Fadervor!
Det er Guds Ord i Barnemund,
Klippe og Skjold i Farens Stund,
Agt det kun vel! i Jesu Navn
Som af et Barn i Jesu Favn,
Føler det paa sig, alt hans Haab
Fødtes af Troen i hans Daab,
Kom saa ihu med Mund og Haand
Han aander Liv i Jesu Navn,
Han lægger os i Jesu Favn,
Lægger hans Bøn os i Munden!
Saa i Guds Huus du har hjemme,
Thi kun Guds ægte Børn har Mund
Til uden Tant af Hjertens Grund
Det Rigdoms Dyb jeg ikke veed
Med al min Sands at fatte:
At hver som troer paa hannem, maa
I vor Natur han klædte sig
Og for vor Arv i Himmerig
Ja, han har ved sit Korses Blod
Min Sjæl, vær derfor frisk og fro
Du kan i kraft og freidig Tro
Thi Døden mistet har sin Braad
Guds Engle i Flok! synger liflig i Chor,
Om Barnet, Gudsbarnet, som fødtes paa Jord
Om Jesus, vor Helt og vor Herre!
Gudsfolket paa Jord! tager Barnet i Favn!
Med Fred kom vor Frelser i Faderens Navn,
Vor Jesus, vor Helt og vor Herre!
Al Eren er Guds over høieste Sky,
I Billedet sit har han skabt os paany,
Med Jesus, vor Helt og vor Herre!
I Verden er der Suk og Savn,
Paa dem veed Himlen intet Navn,
Hvor vi hos ham er hjemme,
Paa Jorden er der Strid og Had,
Paa Jorden er der Rang og Skam,
Forklared' staae vi frem for ham,
Tidt min Aand sig lod forvilde
Hver min Synd staaer for dit Øie
Til mig selv jeg seer med Blusel,
O! hvad kan den Byrde lette,
Som saa dybt mig trykker ned?
Trøst og Haab og Mod forsvinde.
Hvor? Ak hvor er Hielp at finde?
Hvo vil mig det Haab betage,
Du mig gavst i Liv og Død?
Lad din gode Aand mig lede,
At for Synd jeg vogter mig;
Giv at jeg er altid rede
Til at troe og lyde dig!
Et Kors det var det haarde, trange Leie,
Som Jordens Børn gav Frelseren i Eie;
Kun Had til Bolster og kun Haan til Hynde
Fik han, der ikke kjendte til at synde.
Nu vaier Korset høit i Folkets Banner,
Og By ved By en Korsets Kirke stander!
Mod gyldne Kors sig Aftensolen bryder,
Og Korsets Ord fra tusind Tunger lyder.
I Kirkens Korsgang for det høie Alter
Der mødes Ung og Gammel, Fløil og Pjalter!
I Kirkens Korsgang under ranke Søiler
Gaaer Klang af Daabens Vand og Gravens Nøgler.
Ja, Korset kneiser over Land og Bølge,
Og hvo vil ikke Jesu Indtog følge?
Og Alle komme de med Palmegrene,
Men hvo vil være Simon af Cyrene?
Det er saa let at lægge Kors paa Andre,
Det er saa tungt med Korset selv at vandre;
Men vil du favne ham i Aftenfreden,
Saa maa du følge ham i Middagsheden.
Vel dig, som gik med ham i Livets Trængsler!
For dig gaaer Dødens Port paa lette Hængsler!
Vel mig, om Stav jeg kan af Korset skære,
Da gaaer jeg let, hvor Veiene er svære!
Lov og Tak og evig Priis
Let er Byrden, Gud mig gav,
Lys nu, Kors, og straal nu, Grav,
O, at jeg havde tusind Tunger,
Hvor skulde Sjælens Lyst og Hunger
Til Gud at prise denne Gang
Og mætte sig i Herrens Priis!
Lad høres, hvert et Blad, din Lyd,
O, hjælper mig, min Gud at love,
Slaaer sammen høit til Sang og Fryd,
At ære med mig Herrens Magt!
Hid, al den Deel, som sig kan røre
Og drage Aande i sit Bryst
Hid, hjælper mig min Tak fremføre,
Og laaner mig enhver sin Røst
Som har omringet mig saa stærk!
Lov, Priis og Tak i Evighed
For alt det Gode, som du lader
Jeg baade venter, har og fik!
Som lod dig hid til Verden sende,
At lide Dødens Vee og Skam,
For mig at frie af Satans Magt,
Dig ogsaa skee al Lov og Ære,
Din Hjælp og Bistand, Ord og Lære,
For Naadens Trøst og søde Kald;
Thi findes noget Godt i mig,
Det alt jo virket er af dig!
Bort, baade Verdens Lyst og Smerte!
I skal ei trykke meer mit Sind,
Til Himlen svinger sig mit Hjerte,
Fra Eder bort, for Thronen ind;
Al Priis og Ere være dig
Til Jorden kom Du blid og from,
Men Vold og Svig Forfulgte dig
O Jesu! vær Mig altid nær,
Og dan du selv mit Hierte.
Thi see; jeg maa Saa varsom gaae,
Styrk mig, at jeg kan bestaae,
Da gaaer jeg hen Til Faderen
Naar Tro og Haab de skal
Er ei saa let en Sag,
Mod dem, som paa ham troer,
Hun staaer saa trygt i Læ,
Trods, om han tør mig røre,
Hun gaaer sin Trøst at hente
Og jeg gaaer bort i Fred!
Fandt en Vei, sig ind at liste?
Vil Verdens Børn i Kampen gaae
Der visner dog som Græs og Straae,
Hvad bør ei vi da lide,
Bort da, Uvished; lad mig ei
Men lad mig paa mit Levnets Vei
Høit vidner Himmel, Hav og Jord,
At du er viis, og god og stor.
Det vidner Solen paa din Himmel,
Det vidner alt det Skabtes Vrimmel,
som ved dig lever, røres, er.
Mit Huerte vidner meer i mig:
Men og jeg veed du er min Fader:
Det lærte os din elskte Søn.
Ved ham du os vor Synd forlader,
Hvor mere klart vi dig skal see.
Min Gud! du i det Skiulte seer.
Du er mig nu, og altid nær.
O! lær du mig at leve saa,
At for din Dom jeg kan bestaae.
Og styrk min Siel naar den er svag.
Hielp at jeg flux udrydder dem.
Du hellig er, og ynder ei
Den, som gaaer frem paa Syndens Vei.
Og Løn hos dig i Himler faaer.
Hielp, at jeg elsker, lyder dig,
At ved dit Ord jeg glæder mig
Paa Himlens Fryd en Forsmag er.
Naar denne Fryd i Hiertet er,
Thi evigt Liv jeg faaer hos dig.
O Sjæl, hvor blev de gode Ord,
Som Jesus fik, den Tid du gik
Og om vor Herres Naade bad?
Saa har din Mund udi hiin Stund
Men med hvad Hjerte det er skeet,
Du selv kun og din Gud har seet.
Græd for den Tid, som er forbi
Suk, raab og bed, at Miskundhed
Og at ved Jesu Kors og Blod,
Forny med Gud din Daabes Pagt
Hver Dag og Tid til Kamp og Striid
Hav hvor du vandrer ud og ind,
Guds Ord og Himmel i dit Sind!
Den store Strid, din Frelser stred
Den bittre Nød og haarde Død,
Ret præntet i din Sjæl lad staae,
Saa kan du smukt til Alters gaae!
Stille er min Sjæl til Gud,
Til min Gud, som hjælpe kan,
Verdens Trøst kan snart gaae ud,
Løb, min Sjæl, fra hendes Bo,
Træng dig ind til Gud i Ro!
Der er Fred og Ro at faae!
Det er i en Hast forbi,
Nok, naar Jesus er din Ven,
Er dog begge kun en Dunst.
Men du vedst: dig Intet skeer,
Som dig Gud ei tjenligt seer.
Giv i Jesu Favn dig ind,
Han skal dig ei kaste hen,
Er du hos din fuldtroe Ven:
Lad det storme, som det kan,
Du skal komme vel til Land.
Giv snart os Fred med Ære
Og Alt, hvad os er godt!
At du er af Gud forstødt,
Hold dig fast til Ordets Kilde,
Har du gjort din Gud imod,
Ei! han er jo from og god,
Har du samlet dig Guds Vrede,
Hør hans Ord: saa sandt jeg lever,
Vil jeg ei en Synders Død,
Du, som for Guds Vrede bæver,
Glæd dig, det har ingen Nød!
Gaaer du ærligt til din Gud,
Dem, som i hans Naade staae,
Men og efter dem sig skynder,
Og du havde dem og mere
Fyldt med Synd imod hans Bud,
Det var meget, dog ei meer
Ingen Sø, hvor stærk den bryder,
Ingen Strøm, hvor høit den gaaer,
Ingen Ild, hvor hed den syder,
Her er Naade, Gud skee Lov!
Hvem vil pine sig og kvæle,
Al den Synd du mindes kan,
Mod Guds Naades Magt at regne,
Som du kan dig frit tilegne.
Hvad er det godt at lande
Fra Sult og Savn til Faders Favn!
Hvad er det godt at lande
I Brudgoms Skjød, fra Strid og Stød,
Ja Alt, hvad har af Sorrig Navn!
Hvad er det godt at lande
Hvad er det sødt at smage,
Sin Arv blandt dem at tage,
Ja, ja, at see især de tre
Hvad er det sødt at smage,
Før salig han de Grændser naaer,
Hvad er det sødt at smage,
Hvad er det stort at prange
Og see, hvad Skat saa mange
Hvad er det stort at prange
At sidde der Guds Søn saa nær,
Hvad er det stort at prange
Dig vil jeg elske, du min Styrke,
Du giver Hjertet Fred og Trøst;
Dig vil jeg ved min Gjerning dyrke,
Ved hver en Længsel i mit Bryst;
Dig vil jeg elske, Frelser min!
Dig vil jeg elske, du er Livet
Og fører mig paa Livets Vei;
Dig vil jeg elske, du har givet
Mig Lyset, det som slukkes ei,
Dig vil jeg elske, thi dit Blod
Saa lang en Tid var du mig fremmed,
Du som dog først mig havde kjær,
Langt borte ledte jeg om Hjemmet,
Som var med dig mig ganske nær;
Er der, hvor du er med.
Forkast da Barnet ei, som kommer
Til Hjemmet paa sin trætte Fod,
Og som i Verdens korte Sommer
Trods al dens Pragt dog nu forstod,
At kun i din den faste Borg
Dig vil jeg elske og tilbede,
Min Herre Gud og Broder kjær!
Er Verden end med Spot tilrede,
Og skal jeg Nød kun friste her,
Dig vil jeg elske, Frelser min!
Priis Gud med Sang, Priis ham, o Menneske!
Han hævede dig høit til Aanders Rang;
Alt, hvad hans Bliv Her fremvinket til Liv,
Syng, o Himmel, syng, o Jord!
Hvo er du? O Gud! hvo ligner dig?
Saa blid du kommer Skabningen ihu,
Ormen du seer, Og Seraphen du seer.
Gud; hvilken Fryd J denne store Kreds;
J Luft, paa Jord, i Haver Livo og Lyd;
Tordeners Brag, Og de lynende Slag:
Alt, alt forunde mig, At du est naaderig;
Jeg da og med henrykt Siel Priser dig,
Algodheds Væld! Evig skal jeg prise dig.
O Gud og Fader! styrk min Siel,
Saa let ved den mit sande Held,
Vee mig, om jeg greb Leilighed,
At jeg mig Frugt af Næstens Sved
Med Synd det kor, med Sorg det gaaer;
Og falder han fra Velstand ned
Du, Herre, hver en Tanke seer
O! skiælve vil jeg for din Dom
Om Gods til mig med Uret kom,
Det skal hos mig ei blive.
Vel mig, o Gud! Naar mig din Frygt
Da skal mit Huus ei vorde bygt
Da giør jeg alle Ret og Skiel,
Og har i Nøisomhed mit Held;
Medbør og Modstorm de skifte paa Hav
— Det er vor Fart mellem Vugge og Grav.
Mishaab og Strid har hver timelig Stund.
Veirenes Spil er som Menneskens Tanker,
Stolt svulmer Seilet mens Lykken er god,
Brydes og briste — saa falder vort Mod!
Tumler dit Sind, som et drivende Vrag.
Selv naar til Glædens de liflige Sange
Sorgen kan komme naar bedst jeg er glad!
Hvor skal jeg trygt Lægge min Frygt?
Bølgernes Sal ei paa Bjælker er bygt!
Skrøbelig' Sind, lad dog være at grue!
Tvivlende Sjæl, hvorfor est du forsagt?
Er der ei En, som kan Veirene true,
En, der har Stormenes Vold i sin Magt?
Hvor du end er, Christus er nær,
Giver dig Hvile for Verdens Besvær.
Søg ham, mens Hjertet saa lystelig banker!
Svigter i Natten dit Roer og dit Anker,
Kald paa din Frelser, da svigter ei han!
Aldrig kan Himmelens Haab føre ild!
Kjærlige Frelser, med dig udi Følge
Smiler mig dobbelt det rolige Hav,
Ængster mig aldrig den styrtende Bølge
Skrækker mig ikke dens aabnede Grav!
Trygt i dit Navn, Glider min Stavn,
Fører mig sikkert til Himmelens Havn!
Hvad vi gjorde, som var ilde!
Hjælp os, saa vi vorde fromme,
Saa vi i din Himmel komme,
Hør du os i Jesu Navn!
Vaagn op, og slaa paa dine Strenge,
O kjære Sjæl, stat op af Senge,
Gjør med din Tak en Himmelgang,
Velan! jeg vil til Himlen stige,
Langt fra min Jorde=Klimp og Krop,
Mit Borgerskab er i Guds Rige,
Der stunder jeg og daglig op;
Lov, Priis og Tak i tusind Tal
Ei har jeg Andet dig at give,
Al anden Gjerning her i Live
Den er at yde alt for lak;
Men mine Suk du ei forsmaaer,
Og Graaden, som i Øine staaer!
Jeg trøstig til mit Kald mig giver
Og fanger nu min Gjerning an,
Min Gud mig end saa naadig bliver,
Som han i al min Tid er van,
Han tager Haanden med mig i,
Og med sin Aand staaer trolig bi.
Og ei paa Verden vil jeg byjje,
Om Lykken end vil med mig staae;
Men alt som Dagen sig mon rygge,
Vil jeg min Sjæl alt minde paa,
Gud med os skal træde paa;
O, min Sjæl, gid kun du vidste
Det maa Alt paa Dødens Side,
Som kun lystes ved at stride,
Men vor Frelser, som os givet
Har sig selv, og dermed Livet,
Er den sidste, saa vi siden
I, Guds Engle, som kan Tonen
Paa den Sang, som er Livskronen:
Paa den sidste Sang at nynne:
Til det Guds Ord, der, som en Sol,
Med Liv og Lys kan virke,
Vi hellige dens Skib og Chor,
Med Ord og Aand byg her en Fløi
Thi bede vi: vor Gud! byg med!
Da bliver her et helligt Sted,
Maa jeg sørje, maa jeg klaje,
Gud, min Gud, forlad mig ikke!
Lad i Graad mig stamme ud:
Lad mig sukke i mit Savn:
God er Sorgen, du mig sender;
Tungt kun Herrens Haand mig naaer
O, jeg veed det, randt ei Taarer,
Kom til mig ei Trøstens Aand.
Gud, du ogsaa mig vil sende
Han skal lære mig at kjende
Han skal himmelsk Fred mig bringe,
Han med Kraft og Haab og Tro
Han skal lære mig at tvinge
Er dit Aasyn skjult, o Fader!

I, Guds engle, som kan tonen
På den sang, som er livskronen:
På den sidste sang at nynne:
Til det Guds ord, der, som en sol,

Med ord og ånd byg her en fløj

Da bliver her et helligt sted,

Gud, min Gud, forlad mig ikke!

Lad mig sukke i mit savn:

Gå ud, min sjæl, betragt med flid

Så vi for dig må være

O løs mig, til din ære,
Du ved min tarv og trang

Hold min fod i din gang!

Det har dog slet ingen nød,

Tænk, at din del er ej glemt

Er, o Gud, din trones pragt,

Giv, at alt mit indre må

Er dog andet ej end nød,

Lov og pris dig være sagt
Her og hist af ganske magt!

De fløj bort som røg og avner.

O! Make me well if I remain faithful to the end

Then my Jesus will surely lead me
To lasting joy.
Even if I am not clean of faults and sins,
Yet Jesus' gentle teaching proclaims comfort;
For God through him is to me a gracious Father,
And forgives sin.
So shall the gracious teaching of Jesus
To me eternally precious and holy be:
Help, Lord, help me to obey faithfully,
What you offer me!
The apostles sat in Jerusalem
And waited for the Lord's hour,
For the ears abruptly it rang for them
Like a thousand bells chiming.
It touched them all so strangely,
It was not experienced before,
They were spoken of in heaven,
Their names were written there.
They were spoken of, as the word of life
Was now to be preached with power,
Of the heavenly joy at the Lord's table,
Which was to begin on earth.
Then on Zion, there was a rush and roar,
It billowed like a sheet,
With power from on high, the humble house
Was filled on Pentecost!
Then tongues were seen like fire and glow,
God's friends they flew in the mouth,
On all people's tongues, God's word resounded,
Diverse, but one in essence.
Then the light from God was lit on earth,
Which has shone like the sun,
Where living voices of God's Christmas message
Were proclaimed in the mother tongue.
And we have until now on the big word
As the children only stuttered,
Of heaven's fire that came to earth,
We have yet received a spark.
That spark, it still smolders within us,
Flares up and at God's hour,
So joyfully it comes us to mind,
That heaven's bells chime.
To the Father,
O soul, do not forget it!
Jesus went there
Through the Suffering;
Think, it was such a heavy path!
When you, like him, shall walk
Valley of death,
You get comfort and help,
And will not walk alone;
See, your Savior follows along,
Remember, he has prepared
Your place with the Father!
A moment,
Then the light is extinguished.
O you, who walked
And opened heaven
And reconciled me with God:
When I must walk that path
Where one does not
return anymore
O, break my clay,
Release me from the hard bonds of death,
Send me your good Spirit,
Take my soul in your hand!
I rejoice,
O Jesus, at my baptism,
And thank you from the bottom of my heart
For the great hope of life
And the covenant on the foundation of salvation,
Which you have made with me
At the gate of heaven!
As my shield I bear before me
Your promise, O dear Jesus,
That I am your co-heir.
A holy life, a blessed death
Meet each other lovingly
Like the gentle sweet song of birds
In the pleasant evening glow:
The two must not be separated,
One makes the other happy,
And embraces very sweetly.
To have fought the good fight
And walked undauntedly
On the path of faith until the last time,
How sweet it is in death!
Blessed is the one who has faithfully served his Lord,
Done his work, completed his race
And may depart in peace!
O Simeon, you man of the Lord,
A thousandfold happiness to you!
You have adorned your time and status
With the ornament of holiness;
You let a glimpse of heaven's journey be seen
Until the last snow of old age,
And served God on earth.
All the world's Savior was your treasure,
You used your strength
To serve the Lord day and night,
That was your only aim:
You passed by all the world's pleasures,
And reached on the narrow path
A sweet and blessed end.
What wonder then, that the abode of the grave
Could not frighten you?
You went to the gate of death so cheerfully
Like a bird in the grove of joy;
You took your Jesus sweetly in your arms,
Then you journeyed in the name of the Lord
To God in heaven.
Oh, Jesus is yet to be obtained,
But he will be embraced.
If we have not rightly understood that,
Then it shall be deeply regretted;
For the soul finds no rest,
for it, in true faith,
sees and embraces its Savior!
Like the morning-red sun of spring
Jesus arose from the bosom of the earth
With life and light together!
Therefore, as long as the world stands,
Now after winter comes spring,
Blissful in God's kingdom!
Like a chorus of birds in field and grove
Praising spring at all times
With their tones sweet,
So let all tongues throughout the land
Praise the conqueror of death
In the dawn of Easter!
Like flowers all in bloom,
As the forest greens, the crops grow,
By the gentle forces of spring,
So everything flourishes in Jesus' name
And bears fruit for the people's benefit,
Both early and late!
Holy Spirit, our Comforter,
Rightfully you may complain,
You have stayed with us in the land of dust
For centuries like days,
You have stayed with us in Jesus' name,
In his, who sent you,
Yet often in his birthplace
The Great Unfamiliar!
You are God's voice on the road of life,
All of heaven's eloquence,
So without you our Jesus not
Our Lord we can name!
But if it becomes clear to us yet
That you can comfort us,
And we pray: Spirit of God, be you
Our tongue and our speech?
Oh no, we hardly think of
That it should be so,
Will you stand for us in the father's place,
We must seek your honor,
If Jesus Christ should secretly
Visit and enrich us,
We also must believe he is in you,
And you in him as well!
We shall not cry out: come to us!
As you were in the distance,
But sigh: despite sin and death,
Spirit of God! Stay with us gladly,
For Jesus' sake, who sent you
To his Fatherless ones,
Will over them, in you acknowledged,
Pour out His Love!
Yes, stay with us, our Comforter!
Our spokesman and companion!
Revive in us every truthful word,
So that it pleases God well,
For he is not the God of the dead,
And live we only mean,
Until you go from God the Father out
And awaken us like stones.
Every time you hear the Lord's word
From our lips of death,
As it was murmured under the earth,
Although it strives for heaven,
Oh, pick it up, speak it rightly,
So we can sense it,
To us came Good from Nazareth,
The voice of the good shepherd!
Every time an honest soul on earth
Wants to fold his hands
In Jesus' name, but the prayer's words
Will die on cold lips:
Have mercy on the dust's condition,
Show that you can atone for everything!
And whisper your Our Father to us,
So our tongues may glow!
We decide on our meal now
And fold our hands
To remember you, our God,
As everything good turns to us:
For peace and tranquility, for love,
For the food of this meal
Of air and water, of forest and land,
We praise you from the heart!
O God, how many wander
And seek for the bread
Whose poor hands are often empty,
However pleadingly he prays:
How many stand in work and wounds,
Distressed and suffering badly
And cry out for a piece to receive
From what we heedlessly waste!
Oh, let us not lock away our bread
Behind locks and bolts,
Before the one who turns to us
Receives his share of it!
Which is collected from remnants,
For comfort in the woe of hunger:
Our number of supplies shall not diminish,
But grow into in grace.
God bless us in Jesus' name,
Who will daily feed us!
We now go to our work and benefit
In the fear of God to serve:
Bless or deed, let the cry of poverty
Our smallest bite not wet
But if only we could that art understand
To comfort those who cry!
When then in the world no bread
Our tongue shall taste no more,
If only then between life and death
We take the bread of life!
If we our spirit in your hand
O Lord, be able to give,
So through death to sweet rest
We could be led!
Lord God of my heart's joy,
You my soul's comfort and peace,
You my heaven here below,
You my life, my hope, my faith,
You my eternal hidden treasure,
Deeply set in the depths of my heart:
To you be praise and thanks and honor,
Whom so gracious would be!
You know me much better
Than I do from the very root,
You have had my clay in your hands
Testing every drop of my blood,
You reflect my all my mind
See me completely inside my heart,
No breath I draw,
I am receiving it from you.
If you do not assign me everything
According to the measure of my thoughts,
If a sorrow stings in my breast,
Which I alone know,
If the sun does not daily
Shine all happiness upon me,
Therefore I will not complain,
You can still manage it just as well.
If even the flame of lightning ignites
The roof that has hidden my joy,
If I myself among dead relatives
Walk with sorrow and death in chest
If my happiness rapidly deteriorates
Into a pitch-dark night:
Therefore, however, hope does not fail,
You, my God, do not let me go!
What you give, gladly I take,
Praise you while I exist,
No chalice tastes bitter to me,
Which your hand will reach me;
Come what can come,
The State of Sorrow or Joy,
Whatever comes, suits me best,
For in everything your heart reigns!
The man in the dust, who is born and carried by a woman,
He has risen from the cave to the heights of heaven,
Shining anew,
Rising lightly above the clouds,
Now has his high seat in heaven!
The eye of dust now overlooks the meadows of the stars,
The ear of dust delights in the songs of angels,
The bosom of dust,
Now is filled with love,
Swelling with the fullness of Bliss!
It is accomplished! so gloriously sounds
My precious Savior's voice.
O this Voice in the Heart spawns
Hope, Joy, Courage and Heavenly Comfort.
Away now all fear my Savior won,
And I an eternal salvation found
Who will accuse me now before God?
Who dares to condemn me?
When I only want to renounce sin,
My Jesus! I am saved by you;
For death's power and the grave's might
You overcame: it is accomplished!
It is accomplished you now sit enthroned
In glory triumphant!
And here you rule millions,
Who know and worship you;
And by your word you lead them
To heaven, their true home.
O Savior! form my mind and heart
That I may walk uprightly;
And live as your word taught me,
And as your conduct showed me.
Then I'll be joyful eternally
With you in Glory dwell.
Heavens, Lord, tell your glory,
The master is praised by the blue vault,
The sun and moon and the hosts of stars
Show us what your hands can do,
But in your house, in your church on earth,
There, days speak of days about you,
There, your sun and your thunder are explained,
There, even the night is rich in enlightenment!
In truth there are no words or thoughts
Who in your house got a voice and a voice,
And as wide as the stars are await,
They bring enlightenment and comfort on earth,
The word with the sun in changing times
Goes forth like a groom in the morning's red glow,
Advancing radiantly along its path,
Crowned like a hero with the evening's red wreath!
So on its path your sun in the heights,
The light indeed, encircles our earth,
Nothing in the world is hidden from its eye,
Its radiant track is never erased,
Pure as a gold is the law you have given,
Converts souls who take note of it
Faithfully your testimony leads to life,
Wise men it makes from ignorant small ones!
Jesus! Savior and Redeemer
Is your precious name,
For everyone who waits for you,
You are also a Savior of benefit,
So your Savior name on earth
Is the great word of grace,
In your name souls are reborn,
In your name, angels kneel!
In your Savior name here below
Is a refuge wonderful
From all sin and from the wrath of God,
From all the soul's thirst and hunger,
From all the world's sorrow and need,
From Violation and Death;
In your Savior name is peace,
Faith, hope, and love.
Therefore, Jesus' Savior name,
God's only begotten Son, my faith
Has embraced with the arms of my heart,
It shall dwell with me forever,
Here it, like in a mother's womb,
Hides me from sin and death,
There it, like in a seat of honor,
Gives me my Lord's joy!
Bitter death pressed you
Our Lord Jesus Christ!
When you hung on the cross,
Al Pine had an ending!
Now seated beside your Father
You high in heaven's choir
And forgive sinners
On this wretched earth!
O, let your spirit unite
Our soul with heaven!
Let men and women feel:
God has had mercy!
Trust only in your Our Father!
Let yourself not be tempted from it!
Heaven and earth will pass away one day,
But never the Our Father will be shaken;
It is God's word in a child's mouth,
Rock and shield in the hour of danger,
Pledge of God's fatherly love!
Value it highly! in Jesus' name
It should be prayed every day,
As by a child in Jesus' embrace,
Where it can taste his love,
Feeling it on itself, all its hope
Was born from faith in its baptism,
Growing with Jesus the Little!
Then remember with mouth and hand
That "Lord Jesus!" the right
Only taught by the Holy Spirit,
Whom all fools forsake,
He breathes life in Jesus' name,
He places us in Jesus' embrace,
Places his prayer in our mouths!
If you then say your Our Father,
The Spirit with the Father's Voice
sanctions you, Jesus' children's conditions
So in God's house you belong,
For only God's true children have mouths
To without merriment for the reason of the heart
To call God their Father
O great God, your love
I can never appreciate enough,
The depth of that wealth I do not know
With all my Sands to grasp:
How you loved the world so much
To want to give your Son,
So that whoever believes in him may
Be blessed in heaven.
In our nature, he clothed himself
And with yours united it,
And for our inheritance in heaven
In slavery he served;
Yes, he has by the blood of his cross
He has now established peace with you,
And in that precious flood
All our sins are washed away.
Therefore, my soul, be cheerful and joyful,
Be full of heavenly joy,
You can now, in strength and confident faith,
Step before God's face!
For death has lost its power
And the serpent's stubborn head
By the woman's seed is crushed,
God be eternally praised!
God's angels in troop! sing sweetly in choir,
Like the first Christmas,
About the Child, God's child, born on earth
About Jesus, our Hero and our Lord!
God's people on earth! take the child in your arms!
Like the first Christmas;
With peace, our Savior comes in the name of the Father,
Our Jesus, our Hero and our Lord!
All honor is God's above the highest sky,
For the joyful Christmas,
In His image, He created us anew,
With Jesus, our Hero and our Lord!
In the world there is sighing and longing,
Of them heaven knows no name,
Every tear shall we forget:
Where Christ, after completing the struggle,
Is glorified forever,
And we are at home with him,
The sigh has no voice.
On Earth there is strife and hate,
With him, love makes gladness,
Anger dare not rise there;
On Earth there is rank and shame,
We stand glorified before him,
His home is the Kingdom of Honor,
With him, everyone is equal.
Lord, I have acted badly;
From time to time I sinned;
Often my spirit has gone astray
Away from you, the Holiest,
Repentantly I look back
On the days of my life that have passed.
God, you know everything closely,
You know me closely too;
Every one of my sins stands before your eye
Openly, without concealment.
To myself, I look with shame,
Hearing anxiously the threat of the Law.
Oh! What can lift the burden
That weighs so heavily on me?
The weeping of sorrow cannot erase
The multitude of sins;
Comfort and hope and courage disappear.
Where? Oh, where is help to be found?
Jesus alone you me Weak
Comfort can in this distress
Who would take away my hope,
Which you gave me in life and death?
Blessed the ine who repents of sin,
And hears your shepherd's voice!
Let your good Spirit lead me,
That for sin I guard myself;
Grant that I am always ready
To believe and obey you!
Then the troubles of the mind will vanish;
Never, never will I forsake.
A cross it was, the hard, narrow bed,
Which the children of the Earth gave the Savior to own;
Only hatred for a pillow and only scorn for a bolster
He received, who knew not how to sin.
Now the cross waves high in the people's banner,
And city by city, a church of the cross stands!
Against golden crosses, the evening sun breaks,
And the words of the cross sound from a thousand tongues.
In the church's aisle, before the high altar
Young and old meet, velvet and rags!
In the church's aisle under graceful pillars,
Goes the sound of baptismal water and the keys of the grave.
Yes, the cross towers over land and wave,
And who would not follow Jesus' entry?
And they all come with palm branches,
But who will be Simon of Cyrene?
It is so easy to lay the cross on others,
It is so heavy to carry the cross oneself;
But if you want to embrace him in the evening peace,
Then you must follow him in the midday heat.
Blessed are you who walked with him in life's troubles!
For you, the gate of death moves on light hinges!
Well, if the Staff I can cut from the Cross,
Then I go easily where the paths are difficult!
Praise and thanks and eternal praise
Be to Heaven's, Earth's Father,
The lost paradise of the soul
Is opened again with bliss:
The flame-sword has vanished,
The green tree of life rediscovered!
Peace and freedom did not disappear,
Humble faith has experienced it;
What the world's wise men did not find,
The children of the Spirit were revealed;
Under the yoke that does not oppress:
Freed Soul God's Peace sings praises.
The burden God gave me is light,
Jesus' voice dwells in my soul;
Wonderfully from cross and grave
God's Only-begotten speaks to me:
The cross became my ladder to heaven,
The grave the gate to God's kingdom.
Shine now, cross, and gleam now, grave,
Shine glorified in the Lord's light!
He who gave life to the dead,
Has revealed its secret;
They shall show the ways of the Lord,
Shall Immature Soul praise!
O, if I had a thousand tongues,
And the best sound of all tones,
How would the soul's desire and hunger
To praise God at this time
to create a Paradise
And fill oneself with the Lord's praise!
Be moved, all green forests,
Let your sound be heard, every leaf,
O, help me, my God to praise,
Join loudly in song and joy,
In flowers, bow your splendor
To honor with me the power of the Lord!
Here, all part that can move
And draw breath in its chest
Here, help me to express my thanks,
And let everyone lend me their voice
To exalt the work of grace
That has surrounded me so strongly!
Praise be to you, kindest God Father,
Praise, honor, and thanks forever
For all the good that you allow
To flow down ceaselessly,
For every joyful moment
I both await, have, and received!
Praise be to you without end,
O you most blessed Lamb of God,
Who sent yourself to the world,
To suffer the pains and shame of death,
To free me from Satan's power,
Thanks be a thousandfold to you!
To you also be all praise and honor,
O good Holy Spirit, for all
Your help and assistance, word and teaching,
For the comfort of grace and sweet calling;
For there is something good in me,
All of it is worked by you!
Away, both the world's pleasure and pain!
You shall not weigh down my mind anymore,
My heart soars to heaven,
From you away, for the throne in;
All praise and honor be to you,
My God in high heaven!
You came to earth meek and pious,
O Jesus Christ! our Lord!
You us from the Sanctuary of God
Brought the Doctrine of Truth.
But violence and deceit Persecuted you
So great was the earth's sin!
Yet you suffered patiently,
Prayed, forgave, and died.
O Jesus! always be near me,
And form my heart yourself,
Grant, I always wander here,
As you yourself taught me.
For look; I must walk so carefully
That I shall not fall;
Strengthen me, that I may endure
When my God calls.
Then I go to the Father
My guilt he has forgiven.
I shall inherit heaven;
I shall inherit life!
Patience is needed
When faith and hope they must
Be tested by much affliction
In this vale of misery.
You chosen flock of God!
Patience must be learned,
If the crown is to be carried,
It cannot be said enough.
To learn patience
Is not so easy a thing,
One wants to be a Christian,
But in one's own good power,
One has boldness
And peace in good days,
But come Cross and Plague,
Then the Courage sinks.
Patience turns on
In the faith of God's Word,
When the grace of the Lord is known
To those who believe in him,
The heart saw all its sorrow
To him freely leaves,
And cries out: Abba, Father,
You are our steadfast fortress!
Patience is given
By the Holy Spirit of God,
When the heart is truly revived
In his bonds of union
The sweet heavenly guest
Softens all our troubles,
And turns the lament of the flesh
For the Spirit's Joyfest.
Patience leans
To the tree of the cross;
When the Tempter appears,
She stands so safely in shelter,
No! she thinks, what will
The crushed serpent do,
Though if he dare touch me,
I belong to Jesus!
Patience is silent
When she sees no help,
And thinks: the will of the Lord
Will never result in evil,
She thinks: it must go,
Who can block the way for him,
However, he is the Lord of the House,
His will must prevail!
Patience can wait,
And time becomes long,
She goes to find her comfort
In heavenly birdsong
In the Lord's garden of herbs;
There her sighs are softened,
There she can pick herbs,
For all her wounds.
Patience rejoices,
Makes the soul joyful,
She goes in bridal clothes
With the crown of gold
And palm branches in hand,
She has captured fear,
She comforts all the fearful,
And loosens all bonds.
Patience I honor
And obey her commands,
A love I bear
For her as for a bride,
God, give patience
To follow me to the end,
Until my eyes burst,
And I go away in peace!
Where has the joy of the earth
Such a lasting seat,
Such a fortified castle,
That one could say:
There is the kingdom of joy,
There is everything good?
Did not sorrow to king's castle
found a way to sneak in there?
Yes, it knew the way!
What is the world's honor,
These borrowed feathers,
This short-lived splendor,
This false high
Which blinds the eye,
Which adore the senses?
Highest up To the top of honor
If I had found the way,
Oh, how little was won!
What is the source of riches?
Pour only early, late
Until you become tired;
Reach the glories
That you so worship,
Are you satisfied now?
Does your gold make you joyful?
Fool, oh the golden heap
Will burden your mind!
No, those glories,
To which guide me,
the Lord's spirit and word
Never these are won
For the Gold that exists
On the entire earth:
Soul, do not forget them,
After these only you funnel,
You don't care about the world!
If the world's children go to battle
To fight for the wreath of victory,
There only withers like grass and straw
What should we then suffer,
As grace wages,
A beautiful crown,
Shall take from Jesus' hand
Which shall forever
In the halls of Heaven
Draw God's honor-flowers!
Away then, uncertainty; let me no longer
fight the storm
But let me on my life's journey
Aim for Heaven's goal!
Only force my flesh
With cross and distress,
O great Vineyard Shepherd,
Until you me
so graciously
Release me from my burden!
Almighty! your divine glory
Shines forth wherever I look;
You, the Creator of all, the Lord of all;
Announce the entire creation.
The sky, the sea, and the earth testify loudly
That you are wise, good, and great.
The sun testifies in your sky,
The night's meadow of stars testify;
The entire multitude of created beings testifies,
that by you live, are moved, exist.
My heart testifies more in me:
Deeply, Lord, I worship you.
But I also know you are my Father:
Your beloved Son taught us that.
Through him you forgive us our sins,
And hear the prayers of our hearts.
He promised us Heaven
Where more clearly we shall see you.
My God! you see in the hidden,
You are now, and always near to me.
O! teach me to live so,
That for your judgment I can stand.
Give me a childlike disposition,
And strengthen my soul when it is weak.
When evil thoughts arise,
Help me to quickly eradicate them.
You are holy, and do not favor
Those who walk on the path of sin.
Only holiness stands before you,
And receives reward with you in Heaven.
Help that I love and obey you,
That by your word I rejoice
That all in the time of trial here
Is a foretaste of Heaven's joy.
When this joy is in the heart,
I calmly await Death's arrival.
The terrors of the grave do not frighten me;
For eternal life I receive from you.
O soul, where did the good words go,
Which Jesus received, the time you last
Went to the Lord's table
Where you sat in the confessional,
And prayed for our Lord's mercy?
Then you would improve yourself,
So your mouth at that time
Spoke boldly;
But with whatever heart it was done,
You and your God alone have seen.
Weep for the time that has passed,
Sigh, cry, and pray that mercy
Will free you this time,
And that through Jesus' cross and blood,
Your confession may be good!
Renew with God your baptismal covenant
Every day and time for battle and strife
Be on guard against the enemy!
Keep wherever you go in and out,
God's word and heaven in your mind!
The great struggle, your Savior fought
The bitter distress and harsh death,
Which Jesus suffered for you,
Printed rightly in your soul let it stand,
Then you can walk beautifully to Alters!
My soul is silent to God,
To my God, who can help,
The world's comfort can quickly disappear,
Flowing away swiftly like water,
Run, my soul, from her dwelling,
Approach God in peace!
If the sky thunders with the world's cloud,
Above, the air is clear,
With the Lord there is shelter,
Heaven has no thunder,
The mind must go to Heaven,
Where there is peace and rest!
If the conscience is free,
So let the world speak,
It is quickly past,
Enough, when Jesus is your friend,
The World's Hatred and the World's Favor
Are both just a mist.
If something could happen,
Which your pious Father saw,
That it would harm you,
You might well go in fear,
But you know: nothing happens to you,
Which God does not deem beneficial.
Take refuge in Jesus' embrace,
He will not cast you away,
Safe from the world's storms
You are with your faithful friend:
Let it storm as it may,
You shall come safely to land.
In the wild blaze of war,
O Lord, guide our sword,
You draw the People's Bow
on this expedition of war
You Lord of Hosts,
Whose name be highly praised,
Grant us soon peace with honor
And all that is good for us!
Heart, do not imagine
That you are rejected by God,
Cling to the Source of the Word,
The Gospel is sweet!
If you have sinned against your God,
No! he is indeed pious and good,
If you have gathered God's wrath,
Rejoice, grace is ready!
Hear his word: as truly as I live,
I will not the death of a sinner,
You who tremble before God's wrath,
Rejoice, there is no need!
If you go honestly to your God,
His wrath is extinguished,
He will kindly receive sinners,
They never become too many.
For he not only favors
Those who stand in his grace,
But also hastens to them
Who walk on the path of sin;
His tenderness cannot tire,
He again in the state of grace
collects more and more together,
Continues to call, to shout.
If there were thousands and more
Of worlds created by God,
And you had them and more
Filled with sin against his command,
It would be much, yet not more
Than the tiniest feather
against knowing the love of God,
Which has no, no end.
No Sea, however strong it breaks,
No current, how high it goes,
No fire, how hot it sizzles,
Can do anything against our God;
Nothing can be compared to
The great flood of the Lord's grace,
To take away our sins
All our days of life
Now well, you anxious souls,
Here is grace, God be praised!
Who will torment themselves and suffocate,
When there is no need;
All the sin you can remember,
Does not weigh a grain

At the gable on the homestead stand the field's golden stacks,
Yet greatest becomes the joy in the Savior's city,
When eternally we thank the Lord of the Harvest!
From man, from the dust here,
I turn my mind and spirit away.
Here life is celebrated as if it were a dream;
A better life I know.
My God, my Father's pleasure,
And only that, from this day
Should Everything and Everything be mine.
Show, Lord! me the way to go:
My weakness best you know;
And to the goal, I can reach
When you send me your strength.
You commanded me, God! to believe in you;
My soul is strengthened by faith,
and yearns for the better.
Not appointed does the man become,
O God, who relies on you;
Your mighty arm can save him,
Whatever power may oppose him.
Help, God! When frivolity rises
Against Faith and Virtue presumptuous,
And mocks Christians' walk
Yes, folly defies thy word,
Against Jesus' truth teaching;
It scorns everyone who believes the word,
Who holds it in honor.
O strengthen against folly's power and deceit
Everyone who believes and obeys you,
That firmly he may hold to you.
So we go forth to glory,
And vices do not shame us;
For sure remedy we know
To promote our true well-being.
Everyone who obeys the Lord's word,
And trustingly believes in Jesus,
Shall inherit God's kingdom.
Sunday is the Lord's Day,
Not, however, as fools think,
As if the matter of salvation
Were a matter of weekdays alone,
But God's light and God's life
The Lord has given us on this day.
On a Sunday, the God of heaven
Began the creation of the world,
Commanded and said: Light! burst forth!
Like lightning, it hurried forward,
So there was, even in the midst of desolation,
A divide between light and darkness.
On a Sunday, an angel's hand
Rolled away the stone in the garden,
Wherein the bands of death and darkness,
Light and life were laid in the grave,
But gloriously rose from the dead
In a Sunday's dawn!
On a Sunday, God his Spirit
sent with the tongues of flame,
Which, despite all bonds of tongue,
Loudly proclaims, fervently sings out
The grace that outweighs all distress,
The battle of light and the victory of life!
Welcome, Lord's Day,
With the great memories of the past!
In you find delight
All Christian men and women,
And God's Spirit most willingly speaks
On the day that the Lord made.
My death day this great day,
Joyfully I go to meet it!
Grant, that I, according to God's Pleasure,
Might behold its Morning Red.
Oh! then shall Sighs and Lamentations
Turn into Songs of Joy,
When God my Faith, my steadfast Hope,
Will grant Fulfillment.
But the Lord's Counsel is not mine:
Perhaps he lingers long;
And I, step by step according to Habit,
me shall advance weary
Well, let it be as the Lord wills;
It is all for my benefit
When I only, while I am,
May stand with Him in Grace.
In Jesus' Name, I advance;
His Message I will await.
In Heaven, I find my Home,
Where he ended his wanderings.
I know in whom I hope now,
Assured by Jesus' Word;
He remembers me affectionately here,
And blesses me with happiness there.
